Gabriel,

I think that Parameterized is a fine way to do what you describe, and
I think that an extension of Parameterized could make the naming issue
even easier.

   David Saff

On 1/29/07, gabrielcooper &lt;gabriel.cooper@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;David Saff&quot; &lt;saff@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; Parameterized is designed to work with datasets that are expensive to
&gt; &gt; navigate, like filesystem folders or database tables or huge XML
&gt; &gt; files.  A JUnit design rule is that all the tests have to be named
&gt; &gt; before any of them is run, and naming should not be an expensive
&gt; &gt; activity.
&gt;
&gt; Hm, good point. My use in this particular case was a search in which
&gt; any of 6 optional parameters may be sent in, so I thought to use
&gt; parameterized to test the various combinations of empty and non-empty
&gt; search parameters (i.e. &quot;sent name only&quot;, &quot;sent city and state only&quot;
&gt; etc.).
&gt;
&gt; I even made factories to represent the expected values from the
&gt; database and set that as the last (&quot;expected&quot;) value for each parameter.
&gt;
&gt; So it was a small set computationally but large enough that I thought
&gt; it would increase readability and usability using parameterized.
&gt;
&gt; Perhaps there was a better way to do it.
&gt;
&gt; Gabriel.
